### 🌟 Welcome to the AutoGPT Arena Hacks Hackathon! 🌟

Hey there amazing builders! We're thrilled to have you join this exciting journey. Before you dive deep into building, we'd love to know more about you and the awesome project you are envisioning. Fill out the template below to kickstart your hackathon journey. May the best agent win! 🏆

#### 🤖 Team Introduction

- **Agent Name:** martingpt
- **Team Members:** (Who are the amazing minds behind this team? Do list everyone along with their roles!)
- **Repository Link:** [martinpeng/AutoGPT](https://github.com/martinpeng/AutoGPT)

#### 🌟 Project Vision

- **Starting Point:** (Are you building from scratch or starting with an existing agent? Do tell!)
- **Preliminary Ideas:** (Share your initial ideas and what kind of project you are aiming to build. We are all ears!)
  
#### 🏆 Prize Category

- **Target Prize:** (Which prize caught your eye? Which one are you aiming for?)
- **Why this Prize:** (We'd love to know why this prize feels like the right fit for your team!)

#### 🎬 Introduction Video

- **Video Link:** (If you'd like, share a short video where you introduce your team and talk about your project. We'd love to see your enthusiastic faces!)

#### 📝 Notes and Compliance

- **Additional Notes:** (Any other things you want to share? We're here to listen!)
- **Compliance with Hackathon Rules:** (Just a gentle reminder to stick to the rules outlined for the hackathon)

#### ✅ Checklist

- [ ] We have read and are aligned with the [Hackathon Rules](https://lablab.ai/event/autogpt-arena-hacks).
- [ ] We confirm that our project will be open-source and adhere to the MIT License.
- [ ] Our lablab.ai registration email matches our OpenAI account to claim the bonus credits (if applicable).

### PR Quality Scorecard ✨

<!--
Check out our contribution guide:
https://github.com/Significant-Gravitas/Nexus/wiki/Contributing

1. Avoid duplicate work, issues, PRs etc.
2. Also consider contributing something other than code; see the [contribution guide]

3. Clearly explain your changes.

-->

- [x] Have you used the PR description template?   `+2 pts`
- [x] Is your pull request atomic, focusing on a single change?   `+5 pts`
- [ ] Have you linked the GitHub issue(s) that this PR addresses?   `+5 pts`
- [ ] Have you documented your changes clearly and comprehensively?   `+5 pts`
- [ ] Have you changed or added a feature?   `-4 pts`

  - [ ] Have you added/updated corresponding integration tests?   `+5 pts`
- [ ] Have you changed the behavior of AutoGPT?   `-5 pts`
  - [ ] Have you also run `agbenchmark` to verify that these changes do not regress performance?   `+10 pts`

- Add output fields to `StepModel` and `AgentDB.update_step`
- Fix `AgentDB.get_step` parameter types

- Updated language and explanations to be more straightforward and beginner-friendly.
- Simplified complex technical terms and concepts to make them more accessible.
- Improved formatting and organization for better readability.
- Checked for and corrected any errors or inconsistencies in the content.
- Ensured that the tutorials provide step-by-step guidance for users.
- added 2 graphics

### Background

Hey team,

I've been a big fan of AutoGPT and agents in general since the beginning.

Recently, we have been playing around with AutoGPT/Agents and I thought it would be awesome to integrate a Mendable AI companion into your docs. So, I went ahead and implemented it similar to how we implemented it in Langchain, Snapchat, and Llama index.

This can give you the data you need to improve the docs and also get some visibility on what users are asking and wondering about.

Ps. I even did a little 🐙 animation that matches the logo, hope you like it!

Here is a demo video of the implementation: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nb299ahQJEU

Please let me know any changes, or suggestions that you might have. It would be super awesome to implement with you all.

Hopefully, you like it!

A bit more background: I am one of the co-founders of Mendable.ai. We are supporters of open-source projects and we'd love to offer Mendable at no cost.

### Changes 🏗️

- Implements an animated AI companion on the bottom right of the documentation page that answers users' questions about the AutoGPT docs.

### Background
* AutoGPT should support the Agent Protocol
* AutoGPT is basically an agent factory, and the architecture could be better adjusted to that

### Changes 🏗️

- Add `AgentProtocolServer`
  - Add `serve` subcommand to run Agent Protocol server
  - Add `agent_factory` module to easily generate, create and configure agent instances
- Replace AI Goals by AI Directives + Task
  - Move directives into `BaseAgentSettings`
- Create `AgentFileManager`, separately from `Workspace`
  - Move workspace setup to `WorkspaceMixin.attach_fs` hook
  - Rename `Workspace` -> `FileWorkspace`
  - Implement `open`, `read`, `write` and `list` methods in `FileWorkspace` class
  - Use `FileWorkspace` methods in `commands.file_operations`
- Remove references to (broken) vector memory & disable tests
- Abandon legacy `tests/challenges` in favor of the benchmark
- Implement resuming AutoGPT Agents (#4105)
  - Add `AgentManager`
- Implement functions API compatibility mode for older OpenAI models
- Improve function scopes and data flow in `app.main` and `config`
  - Move TTS related config into `TTSConfig`
- Rename `AIConfig` to `AIProfile`
- Clean up paths in config
- Update dependencies
- Fix typing of decorators, making them transparent to parameters and return types
- Remove duplicate `RESPONSE_SCHEMA` from `OneShotAgentPromptStrategy`
- Fix & update AutoGPT dependencies
- Delete & ignore accidentally committed stuff from `data/`

### Background:
In the skill tree view of our application, users have the option to select among various test execution strategies, such as running a single test, a suite of tests, or all tests in a category. Previously, these options were represented and managed using strings, leading to potential issues with type safety, code readability, and maintenance. There was a need to enforce a more structured and type-safe approach to handle these test options.

### Changes 🏗️
In this pull request, we introduce a new `TestOption` enum to represent the different test execution options in a more structured and type-safe manner. We have also updated the relevant parts of the code where these test options are used, enhancing the clarity and maintainability of the code.

#### Added:
- `TestOption` enum with values representing the distinct test execution options.
- `TestOptionExtension` to provide a string description for each enum value, facilitating easy display in the UI.

#### Updated:
- Modified the `SkillTreeViewModel` to use the `TestOption` enum instead of strings for handling test options.
- Updated the `TestSuiteButton` widget to utilize the `TestOption` enum and the associated extension for displaying options in the UI.
- Refactored code where test options are processed to use the new enum, enhancing type safety and code clarity.

By transitioning to the `TestOption` enum, we eliminate the risk of typos and string inconsistencies, promote type safety, and make the code more self-documenting and easier to maintain. This change lays a foundation for more robust and clear code handling for test execution options in the skill tree view.

### Background:
Previously, artifacts were managed as a `List<dynamic>` containing maps. This approach lacked type safety and required additional processing to extract and utilize artifact data. With the growing need for robust and efficient data handling mechanisms, there was an imperative to refactor this approach and introduce a class representation for artifacts.

### Changes: 🏗️
In this PR, we introduce the `Artifact` class, a well-structured, type-safe representation of artifact data, aligning with the provided JSON schema. This class facilitates efficient data handling, including easy deserialization from JSON received from the server.

#### Added:
- `Artifact` class with properties aligning with the artifact JSON schema.
- `fromJson` method for deserializing JSON data into an `Artifact` object.
- Updated data handling mechanisms to use the new `Artifact` class, enhancing type safety and code readability.

#### Updated:
- Refactored `onArtifactsButtonPressed` method to directly utilize the `Artifact` class, removing the need for type checking and casting.
- Updated all occurrences of `List<dynamic>` artifact data handling to use `List<Artifact>` for enhanced type safety and efficiency.

This refactor not only enhances code quality and readability but also ensures type safety and aligns with best practices for data handling in Flutter.

### Background
Previously, our OAuth 2.0 implementation for signing in with Google and GitHub was based on redirecting users to the respective authentication pages. This approach was effective but had some limitations, especially when the application was run in dynamic environments like GitHub Codespaces. Users encountered a "400 Error: redirect URI mismatch" because the dynamic URLs generated by Codespaces were not registered in the Google Cloud Console or GitHub OAuth Apps.

### Changes
#### Dynamic Redirect URIs
We've enhanced the OAuth 2.0 implementation by dynamically setting the redirect URIs based on the environment where the application is running. The application now automatically detects the current hostname and sets the OAuth 2.0 redirect URI accordingly. This change ensures compatibility with dynamic environments, providing a seamless user experience in GitHub Codespaces and similar platforms.

#### Popup Authentication
Additionally, we've transitioned from the redirect method to popup authentication for both Google and GitHub sign-ins. This update offers users a more integrated and smooth sign-in experience by displaying a popup window for authentication, rather than navigating away from the application page.

### Background
Previously, the `LeaderboardSubmissionDialog` allowed users to input any URL for the repository field without checking if it was a valid GitHub repository. This could lead to incorrect or invalid submissions being made to the leaderboard.

### Changes 🏗️
This PR introduces a new validation method `isValidGitHubRepo` to the `UriUtility` class. This method checks if the provided repository URL is a valid GitHub repository by making a request to the GitHub API and validating the response. The `LeaderboardSubmissionDialog`’s `_validateAndSubmit` method has been updated to be asynchronous to incorporate this new validation. Now, when users attempt to submit their information, the dialog will not only check for the URL's format but also verify if it is a valid GitHub repository.

#### Added
- `isValidGitHubRepo` method to `UriUtility` for validating GitHub repositories.
- Asynchronous validation in `_validateAndSubmit` method of `LeaderboardSubmissionDialog`.

#### Updated
- Error handling in `LeaderboardSubmissionDialog` to display an error if the GitHub repository URL is invalid.

This enhancement ensures that only valid GitHub repository URLs are accepted in the leaderboard submissions, enhancing the accuracy and reliability of the submitted data.

### Background
Initially, the application only allowed users to execute a single test and its dependencies. The UI did not provide options for executing different subsets of tests, and the logic handling the task execution was limited. The Test Suite Button was a `StatelessWidget`, and the task queue had an overlapping issue when the list got too long.

### Changes

#### Enhanced Test Execution Options
- **Functionality Addition:** Integrated new options for test execution, allowing users to either run a single test, the whole category of tests, or a test and its ancestors, enhancing flexibility and user control.
- **UI Update:** Refactored the Test Suite Button to include a dropdown menu, enabling users to easily select their preferred test execution option.

#### Test Suite Button Refactor
- **Old Implementation:** The Test Suite Button was a `StatelessWidget`.
- **New Implementation:** Transformed it into a `StatefulWidget` for better state management and integrated a dropdown for selecting test execution options.

#### Task Queue View Refactor
- **Old Implementation:** The task queue was embedded within a `Stack`, causing overlap issues with long lists.
- **New Implementation:** Transitioned the layout to a `Column`, utilizing an `Expanded` widget for the task list to avert overlap problems.

#### Skill Tree View Model Update
- **Functionality Addition:** Implemented logic to populate the selected node hierarchy data source based on the user’s selected option from the dropdown, facilitating different subsets of tests to be run.

### Summary of User Impact
Users can now select different subsets of tests to run, offering enhanced control and flexibility in test execution. The refactor ensures the task list is displayed correctly without overlap, and tasks are added in the accurate order. 

### Files Changed
- **Test Suite Button:** Transitioned to a stateful widget, integrated a dropdown for test option selection.
- **Task Queue View:** Addressed the UI overlap issue with a layout refactor.
- **Skill Tree View Model:** Introduced logic for dynamic node addition based on user selection and fixed the endless loop bug.

These updates collectively enhance the application’s usability, giving users more control over test execution while ensuring a streamlined and bug-free user experience.

### Background

This commit introduces enhancements to the project's documentation, specifically targeted at Windows users who may encounter issues post installing WSL. The added content aims to facilitate a smoother setup experience by providing clear and concise solutions to common problems encountered during the installation process.

These changes are derived from personal experiences and are intended to prevent Windows users from spending additional time troubleshooting issues already resolved, allowing them to have a more consistent development environment setup.

### Changes 🏗️

- Instructions on updating WSL for resolving initial setup issues.
- Solutions to fix ‘FileNotFoundError’ or ‘No such file or directory’ errors by addressing line-ending discrepancies between Windows and Unix/Linux systems.
- Recommendations to store project files within the WSL file system for avoiding issues related to path translations and permissions.
